status_message:
Mama Stamberg's Cranberry Relish
https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2017/11/17/564320714/mama-stambergs-cranberry-relish-takes-heat-from-one-of-the-familys-own
2 cups whole raw cranberries, washed
1 small onion
3/4 cup sour cream
1/2 cup sugar
2 tbs horseradish from a jar (red is a bit milder than white)

Grind the raw berries and onion together. (I use an old-fashioned meat grinder. I'm sure there's a setting on the food processor that will give you a chunky grind — not a puree.)

Add everything else and mix. Put in a plastic container and freeze.

Several hours before serving, move it from the freezer to the refrigerator compartment to thaw. (It should still have some icy slivers left.) The relish will be thick, creamy and shocking pink. (OK, Pepto-Bismol pink.)

Makes 1 1/2 pints. The relish has a tangy taste that cuts through and perks up the turkey and gravy. It's also good on next-day turkey sandwiches, and with roast beef.

Photo by Ariel Zambelich & Emily Bogle/NPR
link_name: 's cover photo

status_message:
“We’ve seen so many elder statesmen of jazz go on way past the point of really being able to play even halfway decently,” says vibraphonist Gary Burton, “and no one will tell them.”

For a long stretch of his early performing career, Burton was always the youngest man on the bandstand. He was all of 18 when he released his debut album. This spring Burton became something else altogether: a retiree. And, at 74, still in possession of his quicksilver fluidity and deep intuition, he went on a farewell tour, visiting a small handful of cities that mean something to Burton, playing material that fit the same criteria. @JazzNight caught up with the tour at Blues Alley in Washington D.C., at Birdland in New York City, and at the Jazz Kitchen in Indianapolis, the final stop on the tour.

Link to the radio episode: https://n.pr/2sXh9NL
link_name: Gary Burton Retires The Mallets

The U.S. has the worst rate of maternal deaths in the developed world: Sixty percent of the 700 to 900 deaths each year are preventable, including that of neonatal nurse Lauren Bloomstein. She died less than a day after giving birth in the hospital where she worked. 

Our full story on this NPR - ProPublica investigation: http://n.pr/2q9qCU3

status_message:
More new mothers die of pregnancy-related complications in America than any other developed country. Why? And why is that rate on the rise?

NPR’s Renee Montagne and ProPublica’s Nina Martin have spent six months looking into this story. We talk to Nina Martin about what they found, and answer some of your questions.

The long-running saga over Russia's meddling in the 2016 presidential election has lots of moving parts. Here's an easy way to get caught up on the latest and get some background. We'll add to this album as the investigation continues. 

After President Trump fired FBI Director James Comey this week, Comey's deputy and now acting director, Andrew McCabe, stood in for an annual Senate Intelligence Committee hearing on worldwide threats. In his testimony, McCabe contradicted White House assertions about Comey's firing and his standing within the FBI, and about the gravity of the Russia investigation: http://n.pr/2qaODd5
link_name: The Russia Investigation: Key Players And Terms

status_message:
More women die of pregnancy-related complications in the U.S. than any other developed country — and the rate has been rising.

NPR and Pro Publica spent 6 months looking into why. We found many hospitals are woefully unprepared for a maternal emergency, and often focus more on infant safety than a mother’s wellbeing.

Durante siglos, el paraíso natural de Alto Bío Bío ha sido habitado por los mapuches, el pueblo indígena más grande de Chile. Ante la amenaza de que su gente fuera despojada de lo que le pertenece, Víctor Ancalaf, un líder comunal, decidió hacer algo… Sin importar el costo. status_message:
Chicago-based activist and artist Theaster Gates uses discarded or found materials to make large-scale installations. He walked us through a few of them at his new solo exhibition at National Gallery of Art. "The Minor Arts,” the show’s title, refers to craftsmanship of manual labor -- but his work explores the ways in which that intersects with other recurring themes: spirituality, reclamation, inequality, community and the black image.

"So many of my projects are just a testament to the amount of beautiful and amazing materials that enter the waste stream that really shouldn't," he says.

Find this video on YouTube: https://youtu.be/Qfx3tWMOVVg
link_name: Theaster Gates And "The Minor Arts"

Here’s the story we’re working on now: Susan Stamberg on the Hollywood magic that made "Casablanca" happen.

The beloved movie, which turns 75 this year, was shot during World War II. Amid fears of a Japanese attack on the mainland, most of the filming was done indoors – even the famous final scene at the airport was shot inside, with the help of fog and plywood. And there were challenging shortages in things like rubber, aluminum and silk. (Speaking of shortages: Did you know Humphrey Bogart had to stand on a box for his scenes with Ingrid Bergman) Susan paid a visit to “Lucky Seven” -- the Burbank, Calif., studio where "Casablanca" was shot. Why “lucky”? It boasts three Best Picture winners and 10 Best Picture nominees.

status_message:
When Americans think about race, they often think about the experiences of people of color. Tonight, we turn the tables. We’ll be discussing whiteness in America: how and why the racial identity emerged among European settlers here, what it meant to them and what it means to Americans today. 

We’ll be joined by John Biewen, the host of Scene On Radio’s “Seeing White’’ podcast, and his regular guest, Chenjerai Kumanyika, an assistant professor of journalism at Rutgers University and the co-host of the Gimlet Media podcast, “Uncivil.” NYT writer Rachel Swarns will take your questions and Mr. Biewen and Mr. Kumanyika will answer some.

Subscribe to the Race/Related newsletter here: nytimes.com/racerelated.
link_name: RaceNYT: Whiteness in America

A white couple adopted a black girl in 1962. They debated whether, as a white family in a racially divided society, they could raise her; they then returned her and adopted a white girl instead. More than 50 years later, the two women, Angelle Smith and Amy Roost, reconnected. They're with us now; leave your questions for them in the comments, and New York Times writers John Eligon and Rachel Swarns will ask some.

Subscribe to the Race/Related newsletter at nytimes.com/racerelated.

status_message:
The largest protest camp at Standing Rock was cleared on Wednesday. Some protesters set fire to semipermanent structures before the 2 p.m. deadline.

“It’s an act of defiance,” Nick Cowan said as he watched a fire burn after living here for more than 2 months. “It’s saying: ‘If you are going to make us leave our home, you cannot take our space. We’ll burn it to the ground and let the earth take it back before you take it from us.’”

Vanessa Red Bull shared her perspective: “I think that’s why people are setting things on fire: as a way of a last homage to what had become many people’s homes. A community was here.”

Read more: http://nyti.ms/2l2MxGo #Daily360
link_name: A Standing Rock Camp Is Burned
